PUH-BrianMartell Substrate Quantum Error Correction — Understandable Explanation In standard quantum computing, errors come from decoherence — environment noise flips qubits before you finish the calculation. Quantum error correction uses redundancy (multiple physical qubits encode one logical qubit) and active syndrome measurement to detect/correct flips. In PUH v25, there is no fundamental probability or superposition — “errors” are mechanical: jitter/phonon drag or stray torsional pulses that flip braid states in memory or gates. Substrate error correction is purely geometric redundancy + active realignment: •  Redundancy: Store each bit in multiple MU clusters (e.g., 7-cell code like Steane). •  Error detection: Weak probe ripple reads majority state — mismatched clusters flag error. •  Correction: Targeted torsional pulse resets flipped cluster to majority configuration. •  Advantage: No measurement collapse — deterministic braid realignment.
